default4.default default defaultFlood defaultPreparationsdefault&#xa0;
default4.1 Since the change of ownership
default 
defaultin 2009, Gatwick has, 
defaultwith the full backing of its new shareholders, invested over £1bn with the end aim of transforming Gatwick into a world-leading airport
default 
defaultcapable of competing successfully.
default4.2 This investment programme included over £20 million in mitigating and alleviating
default flood risk.
default4.3 The majority of this investment
default 
defaulthas been focused on the South Terminal, which had been assessed as having a 1 in 20 year risk of flooding. These works were successful in preventing flooding of the
default 
defaultSouth Terminal during the recent exception
defaultal weather.
default4.4 The North Terminal had been assessed in 2008 as being at a low risk of flooding- less than a 1in 100 year risk.
default4.5 Gatwick will be working with the Environment
default 
defaultAgency to reassess all flood modeling, and provides
default 
defaultan unqualified assurance th
defaultat all necessary further
default 
defaultinvestment will be carried out as a matter
default 
defaultof urgency.
default&#xa0;
default5.default default defaultPassengersdefault&#xa0;
default5.1 Despite the lack of warning and despite the flooding
default 
defaultand the subsequent loss of the switch rooms at the North Terminal it is clear that there is a lot more
default Gatwick could ·and should · have done with
default 
defaultits airport partners to help make the disruption as painless as possible for passengers.
default5.2 Gatwick did attempt to communicate
default 
defaultwith passengers via twitter, issuing over 300 tweets
default 
defaulton the day. It also issued thre
defaulte media statements
default 
defaultwhich were sent to key news rooms and media outlets
default 
defaultas well as briefing local and national media throughout the day.
default5.3 As an Airport
default 
defaultGatwick sets itself very high standards in performance and customer service. It 
defaulthas worked hard along 
defaultwith its airport
default 
defaultpartners to achieve a good reputation for dealing with disruptions. On this occasion Gatwick's actions and those of its airport
default 
defaultpartners fell short.
default5.4 Gatwick has offered
default 
defaulteach passenger whose flight was cancelled £100 of high street vouc
defaulthers as a goodwill gesture. The McMillan review {see 6.1) will focus in particular
default 
defaulton how Gatwick can learn the lessons for the future. At times like this passenger information and comfort must always be a priority.
default&#xa0;
default6.default default defaultReviewdefault&#xa0;
default6.1 David McMillan, a Non 
defaultExecutive Director at Gatwick, is leading a comprehensive review of what happened, the lessons that can be learnt and what actions are required to avoid a reoccurrence.
default6.2 David McMillan is Chair of the Board of Governors of the Flight Safety Foundation a
defaultnd was Director
default 
defaultGeneral of Eurocontrol, which co-ordinates air traffic
default 
defaultacross 40 European states, from 2008 to 2012. Before that he was UK Director General of Civil Aviation and spoke for Europe on environmental issues at ICAO. Earlier in his career, he 
defaultled for Government on the establishment
default 
defaultof the NATS PPP and was Secretary to the RUCATSE study on airport
default 
defaultcapacity in South East England. David started his career in the Diplomatic Service and is a fellow
default 
defaultof both the Chartered Institute of
default 
defaultTransport and th
defaulte Royal Aeronautical Society.
default6.3 The Review will be published in February.
